class Solution {
    public int tsp(int[][] cost) {
        // code here
        int n = cost.length;

        int[][] dp=new int[n][1<<n];
        
        for(int[] j:dp){
            Arrays.fill(j,-1);
            
        }
        return costing(cost,1,0,dp);
    }
    public int costing(int[][] cost,int mask,int pos,int[][] dp){
        int n = cost.length;

        if (mask == (1 << n) - 1) {
            return cost[pos][0];
        }

        if(dp[pos][mask]!=-1){
            return dp[pos][mask];
        }
          int ans = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for(int city=0;city<n;city++) {
            if((mask&(1<<city))==0){
                int newMask=(mask|(1<<city));
                int newans=cost[pos][city]+costing(cost,newMask,city,dp);
                ans=Math.min(ans,newans);
            }
        }
        
        return dp[pos][mask]=ans; 
         
        
    }
}


0/1 Knapsack
0/1 Knapsack Problem
The 0/1 Knapsack Problem is a classic optimization problem in computer science and operations research. It asks how to select a subset of items—each with a weight and a value—so that the total value is maximized without exceeding a fixed weight capacity. Each item may be either included (1) or excluded (0), hence the “0/1” name.

Key facts
Problem type: NP-complete combinatorial optimization

Common solution: Dynamic Programming (pseudo-polynomial time)

Decision version: Equivalent to Subset Sum Problem

Time complexity (DP): O(n × W), where n = number of items, W = knapsack capacity

Applications: Resource allocation, budgeting, project selection, and cryptography

Definition and Formulation
Formally, given n items with weights w₁, …, wₙ and values v₁, …, vₙ, and a capacity W, the goal is to
maximize

​
 ∈{0,1}.
Because the number of possible subsets grows as 2ⁿ, exhaustive search is impractical for large n.

